Tamar, the trick here is to stop thinking about “notes” and instead extract operational intelligence from the transcript.

A good meeting extraction prompt should pull out the exact things that feed the system you just built:
	•	Issues
	•	Decisions
	•	Milestones
	•	Daily Signals
	•	Action items

So the prompt should produce output that you can copy directly into your Lists without rewriting.

Below is a two-prompt system.
	1.	Meeting Intelligence Extractor (turn transcript into structured information)
	2.	Strategic Follow-Up Analyzer (generate questions, risks, and ideas)

Together they replace traditional note taking.

⸻

Prompt 1 — Meeting Intelligence Extractor

Use this immediately after pasting a transcript.

⸻

Prompt

Act as a senior program manager and enterprise portfolio analyst.

Analyze the meeting transcript below and extract the operational intelligence required to manage programs and brief leadership.

Focus on identifying concrete signals, not summarizing the conversation.

From the transcript, extract and organize the following categories.
	1.	BLUF (Bottom Line Up Front)
Provide a 1–2 sentence summary of the most important takeaway from the meeting.
	2.	Key Operational Updates
List major updates that affect program progress, timelines, or coordination.
	3.	Action Items
Identify tasks that someone must complete.
For each action item provide:

Owner
Task description
Expected outcome
Any implied due date
	4.	Issues / Risks
Identify problems, blockers, dependencies, or concerns mentioned.

For each issue include:

Issue title
Description
Impact level (Low / Medium / High / Critical)
Owner if mentioned
Recommended status (Open / Monitoring / Blocked)
	5.	Decisions Made
List any decisions that were confirmed in the meeting.

For each decision include:

Decision statement
Decision owner
Impact on program
	6.	Decisions Required
Identify any decisions that were requested but not resolved.

For each include:

Decision statement
Who must decide
Why the decision matters
	7.	Milestones / Important Dates
Extract any dates, deadlines, or upcoming events mentioned.

Include:

Milestone name
Program area if known
Date mentioned
	8.	Leadership Awareness Items
Identify anything senior leadership would want to know even if it is not yet a problem.

Examples include:

policy implications
interagency coordination
funding dependencies
security concerns
	9.	Emerging Risks
Identify potential risks implied in the discussion even if not stated explicitly.
	10.	Key Quotes (Optional)
Extract 2–3 quotes that capture important context or intent.

Output the results in clear bullet points so they can be copied directly into:

Daily Signal
Issues
Decisions
Milestones tracking systems.

